These are your memory: {"type": "action_response", "result": "### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe problem revolves around the limitations of current methods in learning general policies for planning problems, particularly in terms of their expressive capacity. The introduction highlights that both combinatorial approaches (using domain-independent features) and deep learning approaches (using relational GNNs) struggle with learning policies that require complex logical features, such as those involving higher-order relations.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n1. **Combinatorial Approaches:** Use domain-independent features generated from description logic grammars based on domain predicates.\n2. **Deep Learning Approaches:** Use relational versions of GNNs to learn features from data.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- **Expressive Limitation:** Both approaches are limited in their ability to capture complex logical features, such as those involving higher-order relations.\n- **Scalability Issues:** 3-GNNs, which can capture more complex relations, do not scale well due to the high computational cost.\n- **Balancing Expressiveness and Efficiency:** There is a need for methods that can balance expressive power with computational efficiency.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Enhanced Relational GNNs (R-GNNs):** Develop a parameterized version of R-GNNs that can approximate 3-GNNs while maintaining computational efficiency.\n2. **Hybrid Approaches:** Combine combinatorial and deep learning methods to leverage the strengths of both.\n3. **Feature Engineering:** Develop richer feature grammars that can capture higher-order relations without relying on deep learning.\n4. **Policy Sketches:** Use policy sketches to express complex logical features and integrate them with GNNs.\n5. **Causal Models:** Incorporate causal models to better understand and represent complex decision processes.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe collective ideas revolve around enhancing the expressive capacity of current methods for learning general policies in planning problems. This includes developing parameterized R-GNNs, combining combinatorial and deep learning approaches, creating richer feature grammars, integrating policy sketches, and incorporating causal models.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight:**\nCurrent methods for learning general policies in planning problems are limited in their expressive capacity, particularly in capturing complex logical features. This research aims to develop a parameterized version of Relational GNNs (R-GNNs) that can approximate 3-GNNs while maintaining computational efficiency.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we develop a method for learning general policies in planning problems that captures complex logical features while maintaining computational efficiency?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem will advance the field of automated planning and decision-making by enabling the development of more expressive and efficient general policies. This will have broader implications for the research community by providing a new tool for addressing complex planning problems and could lead to practical applications in various domains.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenge lies in balancing expressive power with computational efficiency. Developing a method that can capture complex logical features without incurring excessive computational costs is technically and theoretically complex. Naive approaches may fail due to the high computational cost of methods like 3-GNNs.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on either combinatorial approaches with limited expressive capacity or deep learning approaches with scalability issues. The gap lies in the need for a method that can approximate the expressive power of 3-GNNs while maintaining computational efficiency.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves developing a parameterized version of R-GNNs (R-GNN[t]) that can approximate 3-GNNs weakly at t=0 and strongly at t=\u221e. The parameter t serves to balance expressive power with computational effort. The method will be evaluated on benchmark planning domains, and the expected outcomes include improved performance in learning general policies with complex logical features while maintaining computational efficiency."}

