cal structures, leading to better performance in a wide range of planning domains. This research will also contribute to the broader field of machine learning by providing new insights into feature representation and model scalability.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe problem is challenging due to the need to balance expressive power with computational efficiency. Developing models that can capture complex logical features without incurring excessive computational costs is a significant technical challenge. Additionally, existing approaches are limited in their ability to handle complex logical structures, making it difficult to build upon them.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on either combinatorial approaches with limited expressive power or deep learning approaches with scalability issues. The introduction of parameterized R-GNNs offers a promising avenue, but further research is needed to fully explore its potential. Additionally, the integration of policy sketches with R-GNNs has not been extensively studied.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a parameterized version of R-GNNs that can balance expressive power with computational effort. The method will involve transforming the input set of atoms to capture complex logical features and using a parameter \\( t \\) to control the level of approximation. The dataset will consist of planning problems with complex logical features, and the metrics will include policy performance and computational efficiency. The expected outcomes include a scalable and expressive model for learning general policies in automated planning."} {"type": "action_response", "result": "To finalize the research proposal, I will address the next steps as outlined in the task. Here is the detailed plan and the corresponding actions:\n\n1. **Refining the Methodology:**\n   - Provide more detailed 