y:\n  - **Development Time:** Estimate time for algorithm development.\n  - **Testing Time:** Estimate time for testing and debugging.\n  - **Evaluation Time:** Estimate time for data collection and analysis.\n- **Expert Consultation:** Consult with experts in GNNs and planning to ensure the approach is feasible. Specifically:\n  - **Identify Experts:** List potential experts to consult.\n  - **Consultation Process:** Outline how consultations will be conducted.\n\nBy completing these tasks, you will have a well-defined and feasible research proposal that sets a clear path for the subsequent steps in the research process. Once this is done, you can move on to the next task, which is the **Literature Review**.', 'agent4': 'The next logical step after refining and finalizing the research proposal is to seek feedback and review from peers or colleagues who are knowledgeable in the field. This step is crucial for ensuring the proposal is robust, clear, and addresses all necessary aspects of the research question. Here’s how you can proceed:\n\n### Feedback and Review\n\n1. **Identify Reviewers:**\n   - Choose a few experts in the field of machine learning, planning, and decision-making. These could be colleagues, mentors, or researchers you have collaborated with in the past.\n   - Consider including individuals who have experience with graph neural networks, combinatorial methods, and planning algorithms.\n\n2. **Share the Draft:**\n   - Send the draft of your research proposal to the selected reviewers. Provide them with a clear deadline for their feedback.\n   - Optionally, you can include a brief cover letter or email explaining the purpose of the research and why you value their input.\n\n3. **Collect Feedback:**\n   - Be open to constructive criticism and suggestions. Reviewers may provide insights into potential gaps, weaknesses, or areas for improvement.\n   - Pay attention to any technical, theoretical, or practical challenges they identify.\n\n4. **Iterative Improvement:**\n   - Based on the feedback received, make necessary revisions to the proposal. This may involve clarifying sections, addressing gaps, or refining the methodology.\n   - Iterate on the proposal until you are satisfied with the quality and clarity of the document.\n\n### Example of How to Share the Draft\n\n**Subject:** Feedback Request for Research Proposal on Efficient Planning Algorithms\n\n**Dear [Reviewer\'s Name],**\n\nI hope this email finds you well. I am currently working on a research proposal titled "Developing Efficient Planning Algorithms for Complex Logical Features and Compositions of Binary Relations." I would greatly appreciate your feedback on the draft, as your expertise in [specific area] would be invaluable.\n\nPlease find attached the current version of the proposal. I would be grateful if you could review it and provide your insights by [deadline]. Your feedback will help me refine the proposal and ensure it is clear, concise, and well-structured.\n\nThank you very much for your time and assistance.\n\nBest regards,  \n[Your Name]  \n[Your Contact Information]\n\n### Next Steps After Feedback\n\n- **Refine the Proposal Further:** Incorporate the feedback received and make any necessary revisions.\n- **Create a Final Draft:** Once you are satisfied with the proposal, create a final draft that is polished and ready for submission or presentation.\n- **Prepare for Submission or Presentation:** If the proposal is intended for a conference or journal, prepare it according to the submission guidelines. If it is intended for a presentation, prepare slides and a presentation script.\n\nBy following these steps, you can ensure that your research proposal is well-prepared and ready for the next phase.'}, 'task_results': [{'agent1': "Result from the model:To draft the formal research proposal document, I will follow the structured plan provided and ensure each section is clear, coherent, and complete. Here is the detailed draft:\n\n---\n\n**Title:** Developing a Scalable and Expressive Model for Learning General Policies in Automated Planning Using Parameterized R-GNNs and Policy Sketches\n\n**Abstract:**\nThis research aims to develop a scalable and expressive model for learning general policies in automated planning that can handle complex logical features. The proposed approach involves developing a parameterized version of R-GNNs that can balance expressive power with computational effort. The method will involve transforming the input set of atoms to capture complex logical features and using a parameter \\( t \\) to control the level of approximation. The dataset will consist of planning problems with complex logical features, and the metrics will include policy performance and computational efficiency. The expected outcomes include a scalable and expressive model for learning general policies in automated planning.\n\n**Introduction:**\nMachine learning, particularly in the context of automated planning and decision-making, is limited by its ability to learn general policies that can handle complex logical features. Current approaches, whether combinatorial or deep learning-based, struggle with capturing the nuances of complex logical structures, leading to suboptimal policies and scalability issues. This research aims to address these limitations by developing a parameterized version of R-GNNs that can balance expressive power with computational effort.\n\n**Literature Review:**\n- **Existing Approaches:** Review of combinatorial and deep learning methods in automated planning.\n  - Combinatorial approaches use domain-independent features generated from description logic grammars based on domain predicates.\n  - Deep learning approaches use relational versions of graph neural networks (GNNs) to learn features from data.\n- **Limitations:** Highlight the limitations of these approaches.\n  - Combinatorial approaches are limited in their ability to learn policies requiring complex logical features.\n  - Deep learning approaches, particularly higher-order GNNs, are computationally expensive and do not scale well.\n- **Parameterized R-GNNs:** Introduction and potential of parameterized R-GNNs.\n  - Parameterized R-GNNs offer a balance between expressive power and computational effort.\n  - The parameter \\( t \\) controls the level of approximation, allowing for adaptive learning.\n- **Policy Sketches:** Use of policy sketches in automated planning.\n  - Policy sketches provide high-level guidance and structure to the learning process.\n  - They can be integrated with R-GNNs to enhance learning efficiency.\n- **State Symmetry Detection:** Importance of state symmetry detection.\n  - State symmetry detection reduces the search space and enhances learning efficiency.\n  - Existing methods are limited in their ability to distinguish non-symmetric states.\n\n**Methodology:**\n1. **Input Transformation:**\n   - **Logical Feature Extraction:** Develop a method to extract logical features from the input set of atoms. This involves identifying and encoding complex logical structures such as conjunctions, disjunctions, and negations.\n   - **Graph Construction:** Convert the extracted logical features into a graph representation where nodes represent atoms and edges represent logical relationships between them.\n2. **Parameter \\( t \\) Control:**\n   - **Approximation Levels:** Define different levels of approximation controlled by the parameter \\( t \\). Lower values of \\( t \\) will result in more detailed and expressive representations, while higher values will provide more generalized and computationally efficient models.\n   - **Adaptive Learning:** Implement an adaptive learning mechanism that adjusts the parameter \\( t \\) based on the complexity of the input problem and the desired balance between expressiveness and efficiency.\n3. **Model Training:**\n   - **Parameterized R-GNNs:** Train the parameterized R-GNNs using the transformed input graphs. The model should be able to learn complex logical features while maintaining computational efficiency.\n   - **Policy Sketch Integration:** Integrate policy sketches to guide the learning process. Use policy sketches to provide high-level guidance and structure to the learning process, allowing the R-GNNs to focus on capturing the nuances of the logical features.\n4. **Model Evaluation:**\n   - **Performance Metrics:** Evaluate the model using a set of predefined metrics, including policy performance, computational efficiency, and scalability.\n   - **Iterative Improvement:** Use the evaluation results to iteratively improve the model. Adjust the parameter \\( t \\) and refine the input transformation techniques based on the evaluation results.\n\n**Datasets:**\n- **Benchmark Planning Domains:** Use benchmark domains such as Blocks World, Logistics, and Gripper to train and test the model. These domains provide a wide range of planning problems with complex logical features.\n- **Synthetic Datasets:** Generate synthetic datasets with varying levels of complexity to test the model's ability to handle different types of logical structures.\n\n**Preprocessing Steps:**\n- **Logical Feature Extraction:** Extract logical features from the planning problems using the method developed in the input transformation step.\n- **Graph Construction:** Convert the extracted logical features into graph representations.\n- **Normalization:** Normalize the graph representations to ensure consistency and improve model performance.\n\n**Evaluation Metrics:**\n- **Policy Performance:**\n  - **Success Rate:** Measure the percentage of planning problems solved successfully by the model.\n  - **Solution Quality:** Evaluate the quality of the solutions generated by the model, including the length and efficiency of the plans.\n- **Computational Efficiency:**\n  - **Training Time:** Measure the time taken to train the model on the dataset.\n  - **Inference Time:** Measure the time taken to generate a plan for a new planning problem.\n- **Scalability:**\n  - **Problem Size:** Evaluate the model's ability to handle planning problems of varying sizes.\n  - **Logical Complexity:** Evaluate the model's ability to handle planning problems with varying levels of logical complexity.\n\n**Expected Outcomes:**\n- **Scalable and Expressive Model:** Demonstrate that the proposed approach can develop a scalable and expressive model for learning general policies in automated planning that can handle complex logical features. Show that the model can achieve high success rates and solution quality on benchmark planning domains.\n- **Balanced Expressiveness and Efficiency:** Demonstrate that the model can balance expressive power with computational efficiency by adjusting the parameter \\( t \\). Show that the model can handle complex logical structures without incurring excessive computational costs.\n- **Iterative Improvement:** Demonstrate that the model can be iteratively improved using the evaluation results. Show that the adaptive learning mechanism can adjust the parameter \\( t \\) and refine the input transformation techniques based on the evaluation results.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n- **Summary:** Summarize the key points of the research.\n- **Future Work:** Discuss potential future research directions, such as extending the model to handle more complex planning domains and exploring the integration of additional techniques for feature extraction and graph construction.\n\n**References:**\n- Include all relevant references cited in the proposal.\n\n---\n\nThis draft provides a structured and comprehensive overview of the research proposal. The next step is to refine each section further, ensuring clarity, coherence, and completeness.\n"}, {'agent2': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Successfully completed session ab7ad348-155e-4539-b819-380c6e08397c", "full_chat_history": "In Session ab7ad348-155e-4539-b819-380c6e08397c \\nFrom