ting feedback, and the next steps for refining and finalizing the research proposal."}'}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can we develop a scalable and expressive model for learning general policies in automated planning that can handle complex logical features and compositions of binary relations, while maintaining computational efficiency?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for advancing automated planning systems to handle more complex and realistic scenarios. It will enable better performance in domains requiring intricate logical reasoning and composition of relations, such as logistics and grid navigation. This research will contribute to the broader field of machine learning by providing a new approach to balancing expressive power and computational efficiency, potentially leading to practical applications in robotics, autonomous systems, and decision-making processes.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "The challenge lies in creating a model that can capture complex logical features and compositions of binary relations without incurring excessive computational costs. Traditional methods like combinatorial approaches and standard GNNs are limited in their expressive power, while higher-order GNNs like 3-GNNs are computationally infeasible for large-scale problems. Overcoming these limitations requires innovative techniques for feature transformation and efficient message passing mechanisms.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has focused on either enhancing expressive power (e.g., using richer grammars or higher-order GNNs) or maintaining computational efficiency (e.g., using standard GNNs), but not both simultaneously. The gap arises from the trade-off between expressive power and computational complexity, which has not been adequately addressed. Our approach aims to bridge this gap by introducing a parameterized version of R-GNNs that can adjust the level of approximation based on the problem\'s requirements.",\n\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed methodology involves developing a parameterized version of R-GNNs (R-GNN[t]) that can approximate 3-GNNs while maintaining computational efficiency. The method will transform the input set of atoms to capture complex logical features and use a parameter t to control the level of approximation. The dataset will consist of planning problems with complex logical features, and the metrics will include policy performance and computational efficiency. We expect to demonstrate improved performance in learning general policies for benchmark planning domains, such as Logistics and Grid, while maintaining scalability."\n}\n```', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': ['In Session ab7ad348-155e-4539-b819-380c6e08397c \nFrom agent2 to agent3: Here is the refined research proposal document. Could you please review it and provide feedback?\n', 'In Session 63c310d9-b59d-4da5-9c32-6165685fa6d8 \nFrom agent3 to agent4: I have refined the research proposal as outlined. Here are the details. Would you like to review and provide feedback?\n', "In Session b28527dc-7810-4c4f-90bc-6668c9312066 \nFrom agent4 to agent1: Dear agent1,\n\nI hope this email finds you well. I am currently working on a research proposal titled 'Developing Efficient Planning Algorithms for Complex Logical Features and Compositions of Binary Relations.' I would greatly appreciate your feedback on the draft, as your expertise in automated planning and decision-making would be invaluable.\n\nPlease find attached the current version of the proposal. I would be grateful if you could review it and provide your insights by [deadline]. Your feedback will help me refine the proposal and ensure it is clear, concise, and well-structured.\n\nThank you very much for your time and assistance.\n\nBest regards,\nagent4\n"], 'total